% RESULTS
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
% \clearpage
\section*{Results}
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Info
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Our dataset comprised four deciduous tree species from four sites with leaf phenology data spanning three years (2018 to 2020) for a total of \Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} leafout and 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)} budset observations, yielding 
\Sexpr{nrow(emp)} complete growing seasons (GS) for 
\Sexpr{length(unique(emp$treeid))} individuals. At the common garden location, the mean summer temperature was similar across years with 2019 being the coolest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2019)]}$^\circ$C), 2020 the hottest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2020)]}$^\circ$C), and 2018 in between 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2018)]}$^\circ$C). There was no drought for those three years, except for in 2020, where a moderate summer drought (June-August) ramped up to a severe drought in September \citep{nationalcentersforenvironmentalinformationncei_north_2026}.
The calendar and thermal seasons ranged from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$pgsGSL)} days and 
\Sexpr{round(min(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$pgsGSL)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$pgsGSL)} days and \Sexpr{round(max(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ainc} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$pgsGSL)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}a and b). 
The earliest leafout was
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.min(emp$leafout)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$leafout)]}) and the latest,
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.max(emp$leafout)]} (also {\Ainc}, but in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$leafout)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}c). The earliest budset was 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.min(emp$budset)]} ({\Ball} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$budset)]}) and the latest, 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.max(emp$budset)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$budset)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}d. Finally, annual ring widths across years varied from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$lengthMM)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Bpop} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$lengthMM)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotRW}).  


%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Question 1
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Longer growing seasons increased growth for all species, but varied depending on the metric used to measure it. We report estimates as means and 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI) that correspond to ring width change in mm on the log scale---henceforth `RW/day'  or `RW/GDD,' with days and GDD being adjusted to represent more meaningful units, as described above (see `Data analyses' section in Methods for more details).
Warmer thermal seasons increased growth for Paper birch (\textit{Betula papyrifera}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]} RW/GDD), Grey birch (\textit{Betula populifolia}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]} RW/GDD), and Yellow birch (\textit{Betula alleghaniensis}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, UI: 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])} RW/GDD), grey alder (\textit{Alnus incana}) trended in the same direction
($\beta =$ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]} RW/GDD); Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}a and e; Table\ref{tab:wc_slope_table}).
Unlike its response to warmer thermal season, {\Ainc} grew more with longer calendar seasons ($\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "A. incana")])}, UI: 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "A. incana")])},
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "A. incana")])} RW/day). {\Bpap} also grew more with longer calendar seasons
($\beta =$ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]} RW/day), while the other two \textit{Betula} did not, though they trended in the same way ({\Ball}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, UI: 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])} RW/day, and {\Bpop}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]} RW/day; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}b and f; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}). 
On a scaled axis \citep[through $z$-scoring,][]{gelman_data_2006}, the thermal and calendar season were similarly predictive (Figure \ref{fig:bsppZscored}). Results with basal area increment (BAI) for the GDD model were similar to ring width (see Table \ref{tab:BAItab}). 


%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Question 2
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Increased growth with longer seasons is often presumed to come from growth in the spring, since spring phenology has shifted much more than fall phenology. In contrast to this expectation, we found most species grew more with a later end of season, and only one species grew more with an earlier start of season ({\Ainc} (one of the two species that a longer calendar season increased growth for): $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$mean[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]} RW/day; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}). 
{\Bpop} trended in the opposite direction ($\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$mean[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")])}, UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$p5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$p95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")])} RW/day; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}). {\Ball} which did not grow more with longer calendar season, grew less with an earlier start of season ($\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$mean[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$p5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$p95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])} RW/day; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table})---but more with a later end of season ($\beta =$ 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]} RW/day). Alongside {\Ball}, two other species grew more with a later end of season ({\Bpop}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")])}, UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f",bspp_df2_eos$p5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f",bspp_df2_eos$p95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")])} RW/day, and {\Bpap}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f",bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")])}, UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f",bspp_df2_eos$p5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f",bspp_df2_eos$p95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")])} RW/day; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}d and h; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}), with the latter being the only one of those three that also grew more with longer calendar season. The estimates were unchanged when using the full (SOS: $n =$
\Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} and EOS: $n =$
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)}) or restricted datasets ($n =$ 
\Sexpr{nrow(emp)}; Figure \ref{fig:wcSOSEOScomparison}a). 


%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Question 3
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
We did not find any clear effect of year on growth (2018: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{ayear_df2$mean[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2018")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{ayear_df2$p5[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2018")]}, 
\Sexpr{ayear_df2$p95[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2018")]} RW; 2019: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{ayear_df2$mean[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2019")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{ayear_df2$p5[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2019")]}, 
\Sexpr{ayear_df2$p95[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2019")]} RW; 2020: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$mean[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2020")])}, UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p5[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2020")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p95[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2020")])} RW; Table \ref{tab:tab_all}), and there were no apparent differences on baseline growth between species ({\Ainc}: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{aspp_df2$mean[which(aspp_df2$spp_name == "A. incana")]}, UI:
