% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
% DISCUSSION
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
\clearpage
\section*{Discussion}
Here we used 81 juvenile trees of four species from four provenances to study how longer growing seasons affect tree growth (using annual growth via tree rings and leaf phenology as a proxy for the start and end of season, SOS and EOS, respectively). Longer GS increased growth for all species, but varied on the season metric used to measure it. We found that the thermal season (GDD) was a better predictor for growth than the calendar season (GSL) with no clear impact of provenance. 

Our results support the idea that the thermal season is be a better predictor for growth \citep{chuine_processbased_2017,wang_simulation_1998}. By accounting for differences in daily temperatures, the thermal season may be more closely aligned to when and how fast plants can grow each day compared to the calendar season, which assumes a stable influence of each day on growth. Thus, the short and cool spring days early in the season count for less in the thermal season than the calendar season \citep{buonaiuto_early_2026}. Further supporting this, when we disentangled the calendar season by using the SOS and EOS separately, we found a larger response of growth to EOS, with little effect of SOS. 

The finding that EOS appears more related to growth than SOS is aligned with previous studies \citep[e.g.,][]{},
% crd7Jul -- I am not sure which studies you're referring to here... The ones I am aware of don't explicitely mention that growth is more related to EOS than SOS. I guess Dow2022 indirectly implies that growth may relate to EOS, but I'm not super confident about saying this...
and has important implications. 
% crd7Jul -- Below, I changed "the most important" to "an important". From what I read in (e.g. Etzold2021), most of the growth happens in June-July and not towards the end of the season.
It suggests that research that solely focus on the SOS \citep{dow_warm_2022,gaoEarlierStartThermal2022,wheeler_snow_2016} could miss when longer seasons lead to more growth, and also that the strong focus on SOS in phenology research may ignore an important part of the season for growth. While studies have long called for more research on EOS \citep{gallinat_autumn_2015,gunderson_forest_2012,piao_plant_2019,richardson_terrestrial_2012}, our results suggest we may especially need more work that monitors how growth and phenology shift across the season \citep{zani_increased_2020,zohner_effect_2023}. More studies using fine temporal scale through dendrometers and/or xylogenesis could confirm if most growth occurs closer to EOS versus SOS. To date, these studies showed strong species differences as to when most of the growth happens in the season. However, most of these research were done on a small number of species and mostly European and/or conifers \citep[e.g.][]{zweifel_are_2016,etzold_number_2022,balducci_stem_2019}. We need these type of data across more species spanning a wider range of life history strategies to better grasp how their growth changes throughout the season.
% emw5Jul -- what do studies find so far? Check Zweifel and others... 
% crd7Jul -- I had trouble confirming how much of the growth happened either closer to SOS or EOS, so I tried to change the phrasing to reflect what I actually know...  Etzold2021 showed some bi-modal growth for some species and others peaked around end of June. But I couldn't confirm if there was more growth at EOS than SOS.
 
Our results suggest different growth strategies between species may yield different responses to longer seasons. Our most ruderal species, {\Ainc} was the only species to grow more with a longer calendar season and an earlier SOS. This suggests that species with more ruderal, flexible life-history strategies may actually take advantage of growing more in the spring despite cooler, shorter days \citep{bowmanEcology2023,furlow_alnus_1997,grime_evidence_1977}. In contrast, {\Bpap} and {\Bpop} which are fast growing, but more conservative than {\Ainc}, were both most driven by the EOS, suggesting that they would be able to exploit these late season days characterized by warmer temperatures \citep{burns_silvics_1990}. Lastly our slowest growth, longest lived species, {\Ball}, responded to both the SOS and the EOS. This points towards a `neutralizing' response where an early SOS decreases growth, but a later EOS increases it, muting this species' response to a longer calendar season. Studies including an even wider span of growth strategies across species may find further differences. Our four study species are all relatively fast growing, which should allow them to track changing conditions better than their slower growing counterparts. While we found an overall positive trend of warmer seasons on growth, this might have changed if we used slower growing species, such as \citep[\textit{Quercus};][]{burns_silvics_1990}. 

Additionally, we used juvenile trees which tend to be more reactive and could in part explain why they grew more with warmer seasons \citep{augspurger_differences_2003,sweeneyComparisonTimingSpring2024}. While other studies on mature trees have found the same result, our results may have been more muted if the trees were grown in a forest setting. We grew trees in a common garden setting with potentially more space between trees (spacing was between 1.5 and 3 meters), 
% crd7Jul -- I asked Cat about the spacing and here's what she said: # We have three groups of plants in terms of shade (full shade, partial shade, and full sun), and four kinds of spacing, 0.75, 1, 1.5, and 3 m per individual. Trees had more spacing in between (the 1.5 and 3m), though I don't think this was standardized in any way. And shrubs were more frequently spaced 0.75 to 1m apart. 
without any shade cloth on tree species. However, if these trees grew in nature in a mature forest they would have been below the canopy, competing for light and other resources and thus might not have responded as much as we observed in our competition-limited conditions \citep{polgar_leafout_2011}. 
% crd7Jul -- Moved the below sentence from the intro (as you suggested) and put it here as I think it transitions nicely to the following paragraph
While juvenile trees store little carbon compared to their adult forms, they are crucial for forest regeneration capacity and range expansion \citep{luu_importance_2024}. 

Our focus on juvenile trees may suggest how forests regrow with the longer warmer seasons of anthropogenic climate change. 
While many plant phenology studies find invasive species appear more responsive to spring warming \citep{wolkovich_temperaturedependent_2013,zettlemoyer_phenology_2019}, these studies are often on herbaceous species. Our results thus suggest more studies of how later season events affect invasions could be especially important for understanding woody plant invasions. Further, the contrasting responses we found across species suggest assembly of native species may depend on growth strategies at both the start and end of the season.  

Our results also suggest assembly models may need less of a focus on population-level differences than previously suggested \citep{cavender-bares_diversification_2019}. While studies of large latitudinal gradients have found lower growth in tree species from poleward latitudes \citep{aitken_time_2016,soolanayakanahally_timing_2013}, we found no differences in growth across a latitudinal gradient of 3.5\degree. Thus, at least across this latitudinal range, local adaption on growth appears weak. Supporting this, we found no evidence of shifting EOS across provenances, despite decades of work finding that EOS events, such as budset, are usually more locally adapted than SOS events such as leafout \citep{soolanayakanahally_timing_2013,zeng_weak_2024}. Yet, a study of the same common garden including all tree and shrub species found EOS appeared to vary strongly by year and shift earlier with earlier SOS \citep{buonaiuto_early_2026}, suggesting EOS may be more variable than currently proposed \citep{alberto_potential_2013}. Taken together these results imply that our current understanding of budset being strongly locally adapted and thus varying little with temperature or SOS need more study. 

Using a rarely available dataset of tree growth coupled with leaf phenology SOS and EOS, we found an overall positive response from our trees to longer seasons, which has important implications for models of forest assembly, as discussed above, and and also models of future carbon storage. We found that SOS and EOS asymmetrically matter to growth, which means that how we model these in vegetation and related earth system models may be critical for accurate predictions. To get EOS right means we need more studies, especially on more species across a larger gradient. This could help tease out whether local adaptation of EOS depends on the species, latitudinal range (both distance and how far north provenances come from) or some combination of the two, which could then feed into improve models. 

Integrating our results into models will also require considering how environmental conditions beyond temperature shift across the season, especially soil moisture \citep{gaoEarlierStartThermal2022,li_widespread_2023}. Trees in our common garden were regularly watered, likely relieving any major drought pressures though studies beyond ours have found a connection between later EOS and more growth, \citep[see:][]{gaoEarlierStartThermal2022,wang_seasonal_2025}. For the four species we studied, there are currently no increases in drought occurrence within their ranges \citep{nationalcentersforenvironmentalinformationncei_north_2026,agel_drought_2025}, suggesting that growth may increase with longer and warmer GS \citep{agel_drought_2025}, as we found. However, the positive effect of a later EOS could be offset if soil moisture becomes inadequate for growth, and certainly other temperate regions with decreased soil moisture have reported declines in tree growth \citep[e.g.,][]{chiang_evidence_2021,spinoni_will_2018}. Improved accuracy of future carbon sequestration models would consequently require integrating over more species and growth drivers.

